The opportunity screen
A parcel counts as an opportunity when all of the following hold:

Housing-eligible future land-use designation (table above);
Economically soft — vacant, or improvement-to-land ratio (ILR: assessed building value ÷ assessed land value) &lt; 1.0, i.e., the dirt is worth more than what stands on it;
Not excluded — public/institutional land, parks, open space and recreation, master condo records (which would double-count their child units), and mobile homes (naturally occurring affordable housing — flagged separately as displacement risk, never as opportunity);
Not constrained — no more than 50% of the parcel in floodway or steep slope; capacity on the remainder is already discounted;
Material — capacity gap of at least one unit.

Opportunity parcels are typed vacant vs. underbuilt and sized infill (≤ 5 ac) vs. large site (&gt; 5 ac). The 5-acre line separates parcels a single owner or small builder can develop under by-right rules from sites that realistically need master planning, subdivision, and new internal infrastructure.
